-- FACTBOX-New merger deals add to record M&A year
-- 
-- Mon Dec 18, 2006 1:47pm EST
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2006/12/18/us-mergers-factbox-idUSN1848317620061218

 

 NEW YORK  (Reuters) - Merger deals worth at least $77 billion were announced around the world on Sunday and Monday, underlining 2006 as a record year for the value of mergers and takeover proposals. Below are some of the biggest transactions recorded over the past two days. 

 December 18: ** Norway's Statoil ( STL.OL ) offered to acquire the oil and gas activities of Norsk Hydro ( NHY.OL ) for $30 billion, creating a national champion and the world's largest offshore operator. ** U.S. pharmacy benefits manager Express Scripts Inc. ( ESRX.O ) offered to buy rival Caremark RX CMX.N for $26 billion, threatening a deal Caremark struck last month with drugstore chain CVS Corp. ( CVS.N ). ** Orthopedic device maker Biomet Inc. BMET.O agreed to be acquired for $10.9 billion by a private equity consortium that includes affiliates of Blackstone Group BG.UL, Goldman Sachs Capital Partners, Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. KKR.UL and TPG TPG.UL. ** BCE Inc. ( BCE.N )( BCE.TO ) will sell its satellite services unit, Telesat Canada, to Loral Space & Communications Inc. ( LORL.O ) and PSP Investments for C$3.25 billion (US$2.8 million), net of debt, as the telecommunications company returns its focus to its core business. ** ElkCorp ELK.N agreed to be taken private by buyout firm Carlyle Group CYL.UL for $38 a share, a 6 percent premium to the roofing and building products maker's closing share price on Friday. The $1 billion deal includes the assumption of $173 million of debt, ElkCorp said. ** Smith & Wesson Corp. ( SWC.N ) will buy privately held gun maker Thompson/Center Arms Inc. for $102 million. December 17: ** Realogy Corp. ( H.N ), the former Cendant Corp. real estate company known for its Coldwell Banker franchise, agreed to be bought by private equity firm Apollo Group for $6.65 billion, plus debt and other liabilities. ** Mining equipment maker Bucyrus International Inc. BUCY.O will buy DBT GmbH, a unit of German coal mining group RAG RUHR.UL, for $731 million in cash and stock.